04450nam a22005895i 9780822393429DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223934297 a10.1515/97808223934292doi  a(DE-B1597)553465  a(OCoLC)1170373775  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGV706.34 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.4831 aJoo, Rachael Miyung, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTransnational Sport :bGender, Media, and Global Korea /cRachael Miyung Joo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b18 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction: Manufacturing Koreanness through Transnational Sport -- t1. To Be a Global Player: Sport and Korean Developmental Nationalisms -- t2. A Leveraged Playing Field: U.S. Multiculturalism and Korean Athletes -- t3. Playing Hard Ball: The Athletic Body and Korean/American Masculinities -- t4. Traveling Ladies: Neoliberalism and the Female Athlete -- t5. Nation Love: The Feminized Publics of the Korean World Cup -- t6. Home Field Advantage: Nation, Race, and Transnational Media Sport in Los Angeles's Koreatown -- t7. Generations Connect: Discourses of Generation and the Emergence of Transnational Youth Cultures -- tConclusion: The Political Potentiality of Sport -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on ethnographic research in Seoul and Los Angeles, Transnational Sport tells how sports shape experiences of global Koreanness, and how those experiences are affected by national cultures. Rachael Miyung Joo focuses on superstar Korean athletes and sporting events produced for transnational media consumption. She explains how Korean athletes who achieve success on the world stage represent a powerful, globalized Korea for Koreans within the country and those in the diaspora. Celebrity Korean women athletes are highly visible in the Ladies Professional Golf Association. In the media, these young golfers are represented as daughters to be protected within the patriarchal Korean family and as hypersexualized Asian women with commercial appeal. Meanwhile, the hard-muscled bodies of male athletes, such as Korean baseball and soccer players, symbolize Korean masculine dominance in the global capitalist arena. Turning from particular athletes to a mega-event, Joo discusses the 2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/Japan, a watershed moment in recent Korean history. New ideas of global Koreanness coalesced around this momentous event. Women and youth assumed newly prominent roles in Korean culture, and, Joo suggests, new models of public culture emerged as thousands of individuals were joined by a shared purpose.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aMass media and sportszKorea. 0aMass media and sportszUnited States. 0aNationalism and sportszKorea. 0aNationalism and sportszUnited States. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszKorea. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393429zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393429.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles